–1271":"1216–1271","1250–1316":"1250–1316","1269–Female":"1269–Deceased","1203–1236":"1203–1236","1210–1257":"1210–1257","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1316":"1316","1227":"1227","1216":"1216","10 September 1316":"10 September 1316","1236":"1236","1269":"1269","1203":"1203","1257":"1257","1233":"1233","1210":"1210","12 September 1316":"12 September 1316","Ireland":"Ireland","Laraghbryan, Maynooth, County Kildare, Ireland":"Maynooth, County Kildare, Ireland","Athy, County Kildare, Ireland":"Athy, County Kildare, Ireland","County Mayo, Ireland":"County Mayo, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"St","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  French: habitational name from any of the places so called, for example in Normandy, named from a religious dedication to a (male) St. Clair.","2  North American variant spelling of   St  .   Claire  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Claire","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Clare  .","Variant of   Clair  , an altered form of German   Klare  .","French: variant of   Clair  ."]}]},{"name":"Michael","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, German, Dutch, Jewish, and Greek: from the personal name <i>Michael</i>, ultimately from Hebrew <i>Mika’el</i> ‘Who is like God?’. This was borne by an archangel in the Bible, the protector of Israel (Daniel 10:13, 12:1; Rev. 12:7). In Christian tradition, Michael was regarded as the warrior archangel, conqueror of Satan, and the personal name was correspondingly popular throughout Europe, especially in knightly and military families. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian <b>Mihály</b> (see   Mihaly  ), Czech and Slovak   Michal  , Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic   Mikhael   and   Mikhail  , and also patronymics and other derivatives from these names, e.g. Greek   Papamichael  , its cognate <b>Papamichalis</b>, and   Michaelides  , Serbian <b>Mihajlović</b> (see   Mihajlovic  ), and Slovenian <b>Mihelčič</b> (see   Mihelcic  ). Compare   Mikeal  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Miceli","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Sal, Vito, Mario, Giuseppe, Luciano, Rosario, Santo, Arturo, Carlo, Giuseppi, Luca, Paolo, Pasquale, Salvador, Aida, Alfredo, Augusto, Ildo, Lino, Marta.","Italian (southern): from a southern variant of the personal name <i>Michele</i> (see   Michael  )."]},{"name":"Micek","meanings":["Czech (<b>Míček</b> and <b>Miček</b>), Slovak (<b>Miček</b>), and Polish: from a pet form of personal names <i>Michal</i>, <i>Michał</i>, equivalents of   Michael  , or <i>Mikuláš</i>, <i>Mikołaj</i>, equivalents of   Nicholas  . Compare   Mica  ."]},{"name":"Mich","meanings":["Polish: from a short form of any of various personal names such as <i>Michał</i> (see   Michael  ) or <i>Mikołaj</i> (see   Nicholas  ).","German (Rhineland-Palatinate): unexplained.","English: variant of   Mitch   3 or 4. This form of the surname is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Micale","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carlo, Domenic, Salvatore, Antonio, Ferdinando, Filippo, Natale, Nicola, Orlando, Remo, Rocco, Rosario, Santo.","Italian (southern): from a southern variant of the personal name <i>Michele</i> (see   Michael  ), influenced by the Greek vernacular form <i>Michalis</i>."]},{"name":"McElmeel","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Michil</b> ‘son of the servant (i.e. devotee) of Saint Michael’. The surname contains an earlier borrowing of the Biblical personal name   Michael  , before the lengthened vowels of the modern Irish Gaelic form <i>Mícheál</i>."]},{"name":"McMichael","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Mhichíl</b>, a patronymic from a Gaelic form of the personal name   Michael  . This was the usual shortened Anglicized form of <i>Mac Gille Michil</i> in Scotland."]},{"name":"Mical","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Janina, Jerzy, Mieczyslaw, Zygmund.","Polish (<b>Micał</b>): from a vernacular form of the personal name <i>Michał</i> (see   Michael  ) or <i>Mikołaj</i> (see   Nicholas  )."]},{"name":"Michaeli","meanings":["German and French: Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from the personal name   Michael  ."]},{"name":"Mica","meanings":["Czech (mainly <b>Míča</b>, also <b>Miča</b>) and Slovak (<b>Miča</b>): from <i>Mica</i> and <i>Miča</i>, pet forms of the personal name <i>Michal</i>, an equivalent of   Michael  , or <i>Mikuláš</i>, an equivalent of   Nicholas  .","Romanian: from a female personal name derived from the adjective <i>mic</i>, feminine <i>mică</i> ‘small, short’."]},{"name":"Mihaly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Balint, Tamas, Zoltan.","Hungarian (<b>Mihály</b>): from the personal name <i>Mihály</i>, Hungarian form of   Michael  .","In some cases also an Americanized form of Croatian <b>Mihalj</b> (see   Mihal  ), a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Rohese","type":"FIRST","meanings":["An old British name. It is found Latinised Rhesus, and is probably derived from the Greek word for Mars, the god of war."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Rohese St Michael was born in 1233, in Athy, County Kildare, Ireland, her father, Richard St Michael, was 30 and her mother, Rohesia, was 24. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Thomas Fitz Maurice. She died on 12 September 1316, in Ireland, at the age of 83."},"et":{"1233–12 September 1316":"1233–12. september 1316","1233–1316":"1233–1316","1216–1271":"1216–1271","1250–1316":"1250–1316","1269–Female":"1269–Surnud","1203–1236":"1203–1236","1210–1257":"1210–1257","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1316":"1316","1227":"1227","1216":"1216","10 September 1316":"10. september 1316","1236":"1236","1269":"1269","1203":"1203","1257":"1257","1233":"1233","1210":"1210","12 September 1316":"12. september 1316","Ireland":"Iirim